==English==
===Etymology===
From Latin [[eruditus]], participle of [[erudire]] ‘teach, train’, from [[e-#Latin|e-]] + [[rudis]] ‘rude, unskilled’.

===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/ˈɛrʊdaɪt/}} (''[[RP]]'')
*{{IPA|/ˈɛrudaɪt/}} (''US'')
*{{audio|en-us-erudite.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Adjective===
'''erudite'''
#[[learned]], [[scholarly]], with emphasis on knowledge gained from books.

====Quotations====
*'''1820''' — [[w:Nathaniel Hawthorne|Nathaniel Hawthorne]], ''[[s:The Scarlet Letter|The Scarlet Letter]]'', Ch. XII
*: At all events, if it involved any secret information in regard to old Roger Chillingworth, it was in a tongue unknown to the '''erudite''' clergyman, and did but increase the bewilderment of his mind.

